      "id": "8bb8f62b9afda3816ac949265a6935073f45c813",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 597,
        "name": "Sebastien Buisson",
        "email": "sbuisson@ddn.com",
        "username": "sbuisson"
      },
      "date": "2016-02-05 07:21:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\nI think it would be better to use strlcat() instead of strscat(), in order to be able to detect truncation and return an error in that case.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "d0f61905dbb82759bb888403f83528ba1e94b379",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 524,
        "name": "Frederic Saunier",
        "email": "frederic.saunier@atos.net",
        "username": "FSaunier"
      },
      "date": "2016-02-05 09:27:05.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> I think it would be better to use strlcat() instead of strscat(),\n > in order to be able to detect truncation and return an error in\n > that case.\n\nI'm not sure to understand your point here, because strscat() does detect any truncation, and if so it will print an error message and exit. Are you considering some other error handling?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "463e659ae6b3008bf62b7bf32cdfa16db155360f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 524,
        "name": "Frederic Saunier",
        "email": "frederic.saunier@atos.net",
        "username": "FSaunier"
      },
      "date": "2016-02-05 09:28:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> > I think it would be better to use strlcat() instead of strscat(),\n > > in order to be able to detect truncation and return an error in\n > > that case.\n > \n > I'm not sure to understand your point here, because strscat() does\n > detect any truncation, and if so it will print an error message and\n > exit. Are you considering some other error handling?\n\n > According to C99 and POSIX.1-2001 results are undefined if\n > snprintf() would cause copying to take place between buffers that\n > overlap.\n\nFixed",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "8497620cc8e7d228acaba87cde2a264efd88e36c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 597,
        "name": "Sebastien Buisson",
        "email": "sbuisson@ddn.com",
        "username": "sbuisson"
      },
      "date": "2016-02-05 10:50:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: -Code-Review\n\n> > I think it would be better to use strlcat() instead of strscat(),\n > > in order to be able to detect truncation and return an error in\n > > that case.\n > \n > I'm not sure to understand your point here, because strscat() does\n > detect any truncation, and if so it will print an error message and\n > exit. Are you considering some other error handling?\n\nWell, it will print error messages and return, but as append_context_for_mount() returns void, we will end up with incorrect context being used anyway.\nSo I suggest to use strlcat in order to be able to detect truncation in append_context_for_mount(), and change this function's return type to int so that calling function can avoid using an incorrect context.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
